{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658706"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20814"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20814"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.73,0.14,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96192"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13689"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78912"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12438"},{"type":"tags","id":"12439"},{"type":"tags","id":"12646"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32969"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96192"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man with advanced HIV infection (CD4 count 50 cells/\u03bcL) presents with persistent fever, night sweats, weight loss, and abdominal discomfort. Physical examination reveals hepatosplenomegaly and enlarged cervical lymph nodes. Laboratory tests show anaemia and elevated alkaline phosphatase. A lymph node biopsy is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most characteristic histopathological finding of Mycobacterium avium complex infection in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Caseating granulomas with central necrosis","Abundant acid-fast bacilli within macrophages","Extensive tissue necrosis with neutrophilic infiltration","Vasculitis with endothelial cell proliferation","Prominent lymphocytic infiltration with fibrosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most characteristic histopathological finding of Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC) infection in HIV patients is \u003Cstrong\u003Eabundant acid-fast bacilli within macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the hallmark of MAC infections in severely immunocompromised HIV patients. The macrophages become filled with mycobacteria but are unable to kill them due to the compromised immune system. This can lead to a yellowish pigmentation of affected organs due to the large number of organisms present in swollen macrophages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaseating granulomas with central necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more characteristic of tuberculosis in immunocompetent hosts. In advanced HIV infection, granuloma formation is rare in MAC infection due to impaired cell-mediated immunity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensive tissue necrosis with neutrophilic infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E - Tissue destruction is typically minimal in MAC infection in HIV patients. The infection is characterized by accumulation of organisms rather than destructive inflammation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProminent lymphocytic infiltration with fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Lymphocytic responses are typically poor in advanced HIV infection with MAC. The histopathology shows predominantly macrophages filled with mycobacteria rather than lymphocytes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasculitis with endothelial cell proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a feature of MAC infection. MAC primarily infects macrophages of the mononuclear phagocyte system rather than causing vascular inflammation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with advanced HIV infection, MAC can disseminate throughout the mononuclear phagocyte system, causing enlargement of lymph nodes, liver, and spleen, or it can be localized to the lungs. The lack of granuloma formation, minimal lymphocytic response, and rare tissue destruction are characteristic features that distinguish MAC infection in HIV from tuberculosis and other mycobacterial infections in immunocompetent hosts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC) infection in HIV patients is characterized by abundant acid-fast bacilli within macrophages.","MAC infections can be disseminated throughout the mononuclear phagocyte system or localized to the lungs depending on immunodeficiency severity.","MAC infection typically causes minimal inflammatory response with rare granuloma formation in HIV patients with advanced immunosuppression."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 373-374."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78912"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78912"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T17:07:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T17:07:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13689"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96192"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonym